text.tspan: For more information, please call 7.10.3MEDIA RESPONSE - ACTION BY THE VESSELWe do not recommend any contact between Masters and the media in the event of a spill or incident, as all the ships’ officers andcrew have the more important duties of ensuring the safety of all those involved and protection of the marine environment. Mastersshould be aware that the media may try to telephone the vessel to obtain information. Our recommendation is that no information beprovided via this channel, instead the Master should ensure that his Head Office is immediately notified of the media interest and/orrefer calls to the nearest MTI office/information centre. Suggested response from the vessel:“Thank you for your call. As you can imagine everyone on board ship is extremely busy at the moment. Our company hasestablished an “Information Centre” to deal with all calls and they have all the latest information and will be happy to assistyou.The number you require is (give telephone number). We now have to free up this telephone line. Thank you.”What is required is a strategy to ensure that the bridge team know what to do when the media call – if they call. This should be apolite but firm refusal to answer any questions due to the nature of their important tasks on board and the fact that the Company hadset up an information centre for this purpose (see guideline text in italics above).7.11LEGAL CONSULTANTA serious incident presents a number of important challenges, which can have long term implications not only on the ultimate financialcost but also on the long term reputation of those involved. Key decisions are required in the early stages of a response, which canhave critical legal and financial implications.Our approach to date has been to arrange for lawyers as suggested by the insurance company. However, we remain concerned thatwe should not, in the midst of an emergency, be embarking on learning exercises with key members of the team. We would havegreater confidence in the effectiveness of the overall response if the legal team is known to us in advance and our methods andprocedures are known to them. We have therefore decided to build into our procedures a first class legal response capability.In line with above we have entered into an arrangement with Ince & Co to build them into our emergency response procedures. In theevent of a company vessel getting into difficulties, they will be retained on behalf of owners and insurers, as part of our initialnotification process.In case of an emergency master can call Ince directly and give them the information about the emergency. Ince will then advisemaster of steps to take in terms of the legal angle.If the situation demands, once master has informed office and is busy with handling theemergency, then company shall communicate with Ince directly. In any case we have anassurance of proceeding in the right direction.The 24 hrs number for international emergency response for Ince & Co is +44 (0)20 7283 6999. This hotline is manned 24 hours aday 365 days a year.Please post this number next to the vessel's satellite phone for ready reference in an emergency.The Ince Emergency Response Team contact details are as provided in the following pages.Masters are to brief the officers about this facility and advise the joining master at the time of Handover.7.12OFFICE CONTINGENCIESThe Office and office staff is exposed to following possible emergencies:1) Fire2) Earthquake3) Storms / typhoons4) Terrorism attack5) Outbreak of Contagious Disease7.12.1EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS1) FIRE: Fire Drills are conducted once every twelve months. All staff are made aware of the following:a) Fire alarmb) Location of emergency exits from the office floor as well as the buildingc) Basic precautions like not using the elevator, protection from smoke inhalation, etc. during such timesd) Evacuation procedures are discussed including problems faced with panice) Office sprinkler system and emergency lightingThe Office building management is responsible for maintenance and testing of all fire fighting equipment and alarm systems.2) EARTHQUAKE: Earthquake Drills are conducted once every twelve months. All staff are made aware of the following:a) Location of emergency exits from the office floor as well as the buildingb) Basic precautions like not using the elevator, etc. during such timesc) Evacuation procedures are discussed including problems faced with panicd) Emergency Lighting3) STORMS / TYPHOONS: Storm and typhoon warnings are issued by the local authorities and all office staff are encouraged toabide by these warnings.4) TERRORIST ATTACK ON BUILDING: In the event of a “bomb-scare” or terrorist attack on the office building, instructions receivedfrom local Police department will be closely followed.
